---

# Context

O.R.I.O.N. is intended to become a long-lived AI Operating Network capable of assisting users across devices, conversations, and ecosystems.

Unlike traditional assistants, O.R.I.O.N. should maintain continuity over time.

This continuity requires a dedicated memory architecture rather than treating memory as simple persistent storage.

---

# Problem Statement

The platform must answer several fundamental questions.

- What should be remembered?
- What should be forgotten?
- Who owns memory?
- Can memory evolve?
- Can users inspect their memory?
- Can users delete their memory?
- How is memory protected?
- How is memory retrieved?

Without explicit principles, memory behavior would become inconsistent across Engines and Skills.

---

# Decision

Memory is a first-class platform capability.

Memory is not a database.

Memory is not conversation history.

Memory is an intentional knowledge system owned exclusively by the Memory Engine.

No other Engine may store persistent user knowledge independently.

---

# Memory Philosophy

Memory exists to improve future interactions.

The objective is not to remember everything.

The objective is to remember what is useful.

Every stored memory should have purpose.

Every memory should be explainable.

---

# Ownership

Persistent memory belongs to the Memory Engine.

Other Engines may:

- request memory;
- propose new memories;
- update existing memories through Contracts.

They must never bypass the Memory Engine.

---

# Memory Categories

The platform recognizes six memory categories.

## Conversation Memory

Short-lived.

Supports the current conversation.

Automatically expires.

---

## Context Memory

Temporary execution state.

Examples:

- active workflow
- current device
- temporary variables

Expires automatically.

---

## Preference Memory

Stable user preferences.

Examples:

- preferred language
- preferred voice
- notification preferences

May be updated by the user.

---

## Personal Knowledge

Long-term information intentionally remembered.

Examples:

- favorite foods
- recurring routines
- project preferences
- frequently used locations

Requires high confidence before storage.

---

## Platform Knowledge

Knowledge about the platform itself.

Examples:

- installed Skills
- connected services
- registered devices
- available capabilities

Managed internally.

---

## System Memory

Operational state required by the platform.

Examples:

- execution checkpoints
- automation state
- synchronization metadata

Invisible to end users.

---

# Memory Lifecycle

Every memory follows a lifecycle.

```
Observed

↓

Candidate

↓

Validated

↓

Stored

↓

Retrieved

↓

Updated

↓

Archived

↓

Deleted
```

Not every observation becomes a memory.

Validation is mandatory.

---

# Memory Creation

Memory should be created only when:

- explicitly requested by the user;
- inferred with high confidence;
- required by platform functionality.

Low-confidence observations should not become persistent memory automatically.

---

# Memory Retrieval

Memory retrieval must be intentional.

The Memory Engine retrieves only information relevant to the current context.

The platform must never load the entire memory.

---

# Memory Evolution

Memory may evolve over time.

Updates should preserve continuity.

Previous values may be retained for auditing when appropriate.

---

# User Control

Users must be able to:

- inspect memories;
- search memories;
- update memories;
- delete memories;
- export memories.

Users remain the owners of their personal information.

---

# Privacy

Memory access requires authorization.

Sensitive memories should receive additional protection.

The platform should minimize unnecessary retention.

---

# Explainability

When practical, O.R.I.O.N. should be able to explain:

- why a memory exists;
- when it was created;
- how it was obtained;
- why it influenced a decision.

Memory should never become a black box.

---

# Security

Memory operations must comply with:

- authentication;
- authorization;
- audit requirements;
- encryption policies.

Sensitive memories require elevated protection.

---

# Skills

Skills never own persistent memory.

Skills request memory through Contracts.

Skills may propose new memories.

The Memory Engine decides whether they are stored.

---

# Providers

Providers do not own memory.

AI providers generate responses.

Only the Memory Engine determines whether generated information becomes memory.

---

# Adapters

Adapters may synchronize external knowledge.

Imported information is not automatically considered platform memory.

Synchronization requires validation.

---

# Rationale

Separating memory from storage:

- improves consistency;
- centralizes governance;
- enables explainability;
- supports future evolution;
- protects user privacy.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Store memory inside Skills

Rejected.

Business capabilities should not own user knowledge.

---

## Store memory inside Providers

Rejected.

Memory would become vendor-dependent.

---

## Treat conversation history as memory

Rejected.

Conversation history and persistent memory serve different purposes.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- centralized governance;
- explainable behavior;
- predictable retrieval;
- stronger privacy;
- easier auditing.

Negative:

- additional architectural complexity;
- stricter memory validation requirements.

---

# Risks

Excessive memory accumulation.

Mitigation:

Memory quality is preferred over memory quantity.

Retention policies and future summarization mechanisms should prevent uncontrolled growth.

